"sfDualMS: Efficient Lattice-Based Two-Round Multi-signature with Trapdoor-Free Simulation.","2","6. We underline several points that are worth noting. First, to answer a fresh query Hagg(L, tj) with t∗ 1 ∈L, W programs Tagg[L, t∗ 1] with the next unused value among {a(1), . . . , a(Qh)} after setting Tagg[L, ti] ←$ C for all other ti ∈L. Second, W answers the i∗-th fresh Hcom query with B. Third, W answers every fresh Hsig with the next unused value among {c(1), . . . , c(Qh)}. At the end, adversary A outputs a list of public key L∗and a forged multi-signature ˜σ∗= (c, ˜z, ˜r, ˜e). Let t∗and µ∗be the inputs to the i∗-th fresh Hcom query. The wrapper W checks the following conditions and outputs I = 0 if any of them does not hold: • t∗ 1 ∈L∗, KAgg(L∗) = t∗, and Vf(t∗, µ∗, ˜σ∗) = 1. • Event AggOrd does not occur, where AggOrd is defined as that there exists a set of public key L that contains t∗ 1, was queried to Hagg later than the i∗-th fresh Hcom query, and satisfies KAgg(L) = t∗. 27 • Event AggCol does not occur, where AggCol is defined as that there exists two different sets of public key L and L′ that have been queried to Hagg, both contain t∗ 1, and satisfy KAgg(L) = KAgg(L′). If all the three conditions hold, then W outputs I, J, ˜w, ˜z, ˜r, ˜e,˜t∗, c, L∗, a1, . . . , an, where ˜w = A˜z + B˜r + ˜e −c˜t∗, ai = Tagg[L∗, ti] for every ti ∈L∗, I is the index such that c(I) = c was assigned to Tsig[˜t∗, µ∗, ˜w], and J is the index such that a(J) = a1 was assigned to Tagg[L∗, t1]. The first condition that W checks is exactly the success condition of A in sel-UF-KOADualMS. The game simulated by W differs from sel-UF-KOADualMS only in the distribution of target public key. In particular, in sel-UF-KOADualMS, t∗ 1 = ¯As1 for a secret key s1 uniformly distributed over Sl η, while W gives t∗ 1 uniformly distributed over Rk q to A. Apparently there exists a distinguisher D, which essentially runs W, such that the first condition holds with probability at least Advsel-UF-