"One-Way Functions and the Hardness of (Probabilistic) Time-Bounded Kolmogorov Complexity w.r.t. Samplable Distributions.","1","[CW79]. Deﬁnition A.2. Let Hℓ m be a family of functions where m < ℓand each function h ∈Hℓ m maps {0, 1}ℓto {0, 1}m. We say that Hℓ m is a universal hash family if (i) the functions hσ ∈Hℓ m can be described by a string σ of ℓc bits where c is a universal constant that does not depend on ℓ; (ii) for all x ̸= x′ ∈{0, 1}ℓ, and for all y, y′ ∈{0, 1}m Pr[hσ ←Hℓ m : hσ(x) = y and hσ(x′) = y′] = 2−2m We will rely on the following properties of universal hash functions. Proposition A.3. Let ℓ∈N, S ⊆{0, 1}ℓbe a set, Hℓ m be a universal hash family such that m ≤log |S|. The following statements hold: • With probability at least 1 −2−log |S|+m+3 over hσ ←Hℓ m, there exists s ∈S such that hσ(s) = 0m. • With probability at least 1 −2−ℓ+m+3 over hσ ←Hℓ m, |h−1 σ (0m)| ≤2 · 2ℓ−m. For completeness, we provide the proof of Proposition A.3 here. Proof: We ﬁrst prove the former statement. We consider picking a random hash function hσ ←Hℓ m. For each element s ∈S, let Xs denote the random variable such that Xs = 1 iﬀhσ(s) = 0m. Let X denote the random variable X = P s∈S Xs. Note that E[X] = |S|/2m and the variance of X is V(X) = E[X2 −E[X]2] = |S|( 1 2m − 1 22m ) ≤E[X] since Hℓ m is a universal hash family and all s1, s2 ∈S, Xs1 and Xs2 are independent. Therefore the variance of X is very small and we can apply Chebyshev’s Inequality to show that Pr[X = 0] ≤Pr[|X −E[X]| ≥E[X] −1] ≤Pr[|X −E[X]| ≥( p V(X)/2) p V(X)] ≤ 1 V(X)/4 ≤2−log |S|+m+3 So we conclude that with probability at least 1 −Pr[X = 0] ≥1 −2−log |S|+m+3, there exists s ∈S such that hσ(s) = 0m. 21 The latter statement follows from essentially the same proof. For each element z ∈{0, 1}ℓ, let Yz denote the random variable such that Yz = 1 iﬀhσ(z) = 0m. Let Y denote the random variable Y = P z∈{0,1}ℓYz. Note that E[Y ] = 2ℓ/2m and the variance of Y is V(Y ) = E[Y 2 −E[Y ]2] = 2ℓ( 1 2m − 1 22m ) since Hℓ m is a universal hash family and all z1, z2 ∈{0, 1}ℓ, Yz1 and Yz2 are independent.. Notice that by Chebyshev’s inequality, Pr[Y ≥2 · 2ℓ−m] ≤Pr[|Y −E[Y ]| ≥( p V(Y )/2) p V(Y )] ≤ 1 V(Y )/4 ≤2−ℓ+m+3 So we conclude that with probability at least 1 −2−ℓ+m+3, |h−1 σ (0m)| ≤2 · 2ℓ−m. We turn to introducing the linear universal hash family construction"
"One-Way Functions and the Hardness of (Probabilistic) Time-Bounded Kolmogorov Complexity w.r.t. Samplable Distributions.","1","[CW79]. Proposition A.4 ([CW79]). Let ℓ, m ∈N, m < ℓ. For each σ ∈{0, 1}ℓm+m, deﬁne hσ to be the function such that for each x ∈{0, 1}ℓ, hσ(x) = Ax + b where σ = (A, b), A is a binary matrix of m × ℓ, and b is a binary vector of length m. Let Hℓ m = {hσ | σ ∈{0, 1}ℓm+m}. Then, it holds that Hℓ m is a universal hash family. We are now ready to prove Lemma A.1. Proof: Consider any polynomial t, and any tD-time samplable ensemble D. Let M be the PPT sampler such that M(1n, r) uses r ∈{0, 1}tD(n) as random coins and samples Dn for each n ∈N. We will show that D is polynomially bounded by pKt 1−2−n. Consider any string x ∈{0, 1}∗, n = |x|. Let ℓ= tD(n) be the length of the random tape of M. Let px = Pr[r ←{0, 1}ℓ, x′ = M(1n, r) : x′ = x] denote the probability mass of x in Dn. Our goal is to show that there exists a polynomial δ such that px ≤δ(n)2−pKt(x) holds for all x. Let S = {r ∈{0, 1}ℓ: M(1n, r) = x} be the set of random tapes on which M will output x. (Note that |S| = 2ℓpx.) Let m = ⌈log |S|⌉−5. Let Hℓ m be the universal hash family deﬁned in Proposition A.4. For any hash function hσ ∈Hℓ m, we refer to a hash function hσ as being good if (1) ∃s ∈S, hσ(s) = 0m and (2) |h−1(0m)| ≤2 · 2ℓ−m. We ﬁrst claim that with high probability over hσ ←Hℓ m, hσ will be good. Claim"
"One-Way Functions and the Hardness of (Probabilistic) Time-Bounded Kolmogorov Complexity w.r.t. Samplable Distributions.","1","5. hσ is good with probability at least 1/2 over hσ ←Hℓ m. Proof: By Proposition A.3 and a Union Bound, a random hσ is good with probability at least 1 −2−log |S|+m+3 −2−ℓ+m−3 ≥1 2. We next claim that given a good hash function hσ, there exists a short program of size roughly log |S| that produce the string x. Claim"
"One-Way Functions and the Hardness of (Probabilistic) Time-Bounded Kolmogorov Complexity w.r.t. Samplable Distributions.","1","6. For any good hash function hσ ∈Hℓ m, there exists a program Π of length at most O(log ℓ) + ⌈log 1/px⌉ that, given hσ as input, outputs the string x within time O(ℓ3). Proof: Since hσ is good, and let s be an string ∈S such that hσ(s) = 0m. Note that if s can be produced using a short program, x can be generated by running M(1n, s), which adds |M| = c bits to the description and can be done in time tD(n). 22 Finally, we show how to produce s using linear algebra. Recall that the hash function hσ(x) is deﬁned to be Ax + b where σ = (A, b), A, b are a binary matrix and a binary vector. We can use the Gaussian Elimination algorithm to ﬁnd an vector v ∈{0, 1}ℓsuch that Av + b = 0m and a basis (b1, . . . , bd) for the kernel of A. Note that each y ∈h−1(0m) can be represented by a d-bit coordinate vector (under the basis (b1, . . . , bd) and with respect to the oﬀset vector v). So d ≤ℓ−m + 1 and s can also be represented a coordinate vector of ℓ−m + 1 bits (and let e denote this vector). We then use this fact to construct a program Π with length ≤4 log ℓ+ ℓ−m + O(1) bits to produce the string x. Π has the integers n, ℓ, the coordinate vector, and the code of M hardcoded (≤4 log ℓ+ ℓ−m + 1 + O(1) bits). On input a hash function description σ, it computes v and (b1, . . . , bd) using Gaussian Elimination and Gram Schmidt, and computes s = P i∈[d] bi · ei + v. Finally, Π outputs M1(1n, s). Notice that Π runs in time O(ℓ3) + tD(n) = O(tD(n)3) ≤t(n). Also notice that Π can be described by 4 log ℓ+ ℓ−m + 1 + O(1), and we ﬁx c to be the constant such that Π can be described using 4 log ℓ+ ℓ−m + c bits. Finally, we are ready to show that px ≤δ(n)2−pKt(x). Towards this, we will prove that pKt(x) ≤O(log ℓ) + ⌈log 1/px⌉ and the aforementioned inequality will follow if we set δ(n) = ℓO(1) = tD(n)O(1) to be a large polynomial. Consider any random string r ∈{0, 1}2n(ℓm+m), and we view r as r = σ1||σ2|| . . . ||σ2n where each σi is a description of a random hash function hσi ←Hℓ m. By Claim 5, with probability at least 1 −2−2n ≥2/3, there exists i ∈[2n] such that hσi is a good hash function. By Claim 6, there exists a program Π′ that on input hσi, outputs the string x. Thus, let Π be a program with the index i and Π′ hardcoded, and Π on input r simply outputs Π′(hσi). Note that Π can be implemented using O(log ℓ) + ⌈log 1/px⌉bits, and it terminates within time O(ℓ3). By picking γ(n) = O(n3), it follows that Π runs in O(ℓ3) ≤γ(ℓ) ≤γ(tD(n)) ≤t(n). 23"
