"Layout Graphs, Random Walks and the t-Wise Independence of SPN Block Ciphers.","2","0. If we expand the expression and divide by α2, we get that β(β + 1) = κ + α + 1 α2 . It is well known that the quadratic equation above has 2 solutions if the trace of the RHS is equal to 0, and no solutions otherwise. The trace of the RHS equals Tr κ + α + 1 α2  = Tr  κ α2  + Tr  1 α  + Tr  1 α2  = Tr  κ α2  . 39 Where the first equality follows from the linearity of trace and the second equality from the fact that Tr(x2) = Tr(x). The square is an injective map over F2b, and thus κ α2 obtains every value over F2b \\ {0}. Since Tr(·) = 0 defines a subspace, the number of α’s the make the RHS have 0 trace is exactly 2b−1 −1 (we exclude zero, since κ α2 is never zero. All of these values are valid, except α = κ + 1, for κ ̸="
"Layout Graphs, Random Walks and the t-Wise Independence of SPN Block Ciphers.","2","1. This is because even though Tr  κ (κ + 1)2  = Tr  1 κ + 1 + 1 (κ + 1)2  = 0, the RHS is equal to 0, and thus the two solutions to this equation are β = 0, 1, which are not valid. The remaining 2b−1 −2 values of α give 2 valid solutions for β, which means that all κ ̸∈{0, 1} have 2b −4 solutions for non-zero α. The case of κ = 1 has the 2b −2 solutions with α = 0 and 2 solutions for the 2b−1 −1 non-zero valid values of α. Thus T(1) = 2 · 2b −4. Our proof of Lemma 15 will follow from Claims 2 and"
"Layout Graphs, Random Walks and the t-Wise Independence of SPN Block Ciphers.","2","3. Note that Claim 2 is already enough to give us a bound on the number of operations required to simulate a random S-box. We use Claim 3 to get an improved comparison constant and get a better quantitative bound. A note on notation. In the proofs of Claims 2 and 3, we will make frequent use of the following notation when computing the image of x ∈F2b under the permutation [k1, . . . , kn]: x k1 −→x + k1 k2 −→INV(x + k1) + k2 k3 −→INV(INV(x + k1) + k2) + k3 . . . kn −→INV(. . . INV(INV(x + k1) + k2) . . . ) + kn. Observe that the first arrow only applies AddRoundKey with the key being k1 to the input, whereas the ith arrow (for i > 1) applies the INV operation and then AddRoundKey with ki as key. Claim"
"Layout Graphs, Random Walks and the t-Wise Independence of SPN Block Ciphers.","2","2. For any α, β ∈F2b such that αβ ̸= 1, α(β + 1) ̸= 1, and β ̸∈{0, 1}, we can generate the transposition  α + β αβ+1, α + β+1 αβ+α+1  using the following sequence of AddRoundKey and INV S-box operations [α, α, β, 1, 1, β + 1, α, α] . Proof. Denote the permutation defined by the sequence of the statement by π. Our proof will proceed as follows:"
